# tenex-edge-dev live lab lessons

## `tenex-edge channel init` is required before `tenex-edge launch`

`tenex-edge launch <agent> -- <args>` fails fast with:

```
tenex-edge: no known workspace in /workspace; run `tenex-edge channel init` or
git init first, or pass `--workspace <slug>`
```

even though `/workspace` (the mounted `REPO_ROOT`) is already a git repo. The
workspace registry (`~/.tenex-edge/workspaces.json`, inside container/profile
state) is separate from git-repo detection. Run once per profile before the
first `launch` in a lab:

```bash
bash containers/tenex-edge/run --profile claude tenex-edge channel init
```

This registers the directory's basename (e.g. `workspace` for a worktree
checked out as `.../tenex-edge-trellis` mounted at `/workspace`) as the
workspace slug and creates the `workspace` NIP-29 channel. It only touches
profile-local/container state, not host `~/.tenex-edge`. The main skill and
live-lab workflow include this step before both PTY and structured launches.

## Running a second container against the same profile WHILE a launch-mode agent is alive breaks that agent's daemon connection

The troubleshooting reference already warns "avoid running two containers
against the same profile at once," but it undersells the blast radius. In
this run, launching `claude` via `launch-agent ... launch claude
--model haiku` produced a healthy session UI (`claude@claude workspace workspace
[idle]`, no `@te_session` warning). Running
`bash containers/tenex-edge/run --profile claude tenex-edge explain event:<id>`
in a **second** container against the same profile while that PTY session
was still up:

- succeeded and printed a correct receipt, BUT
- started its own daemon in its own container/VM bound to the same
  bind-mounted socket path, logged
  `removing locally managed offline agent from channel ... reason=startup-stale-pid`,
  and evicted the live agent's pubkey from the NIP-29 channel.
- The live PTY session's statusline flipped to `[te: down]` and its next
  prompt hung with `UserPromptSubmit hook timed out after 30s` â€” the session
  was unrecoverable; it had to be killed (`container stop/rm` plus
  `tenex-edge pty kill <id>`) and relaunched fresh.

Lesson: treat "same-profile RPC" as a hard stop, not a soft caution. Before
any `tenex-edge explain ...` / `tenex-edge channel ...` / other one-shot
`tenex-edge` subcommand against a profile, first stop that profile's
launch-mode agent (`container stop <name>`, `tenex-edge pty kill <id>`,
remove the stale `daemon.sock` if needed), THEN run the diagnostic command. Only `nak`
against the relay directly (no container involved) is safe to run
concurrently with a live agent.

## The 30315 status content/title stays empty for short turns â€” distill only fires ~30s into a turn

`src/distill.rs` documents this precisely: "The engine decides *when* to
distill (30s into a turn, then periodically)." Turns driven by trivial
prompts (e.g. "run tenex-edge my session") finish in 5-10 seconds â€” well under the
threshold â€” so the published kind:30315 always has `title=""` and empty
`content` even though `status` correctly flips `idle`â†’`busy`â†’`idle`. To
observe a real distill attempt you must keep the turn's wall-clock duration
above ~30s. Backgrounding a long shell command (e.g. "sleep 40 in the
background") does NOT work â€” Claude Code ends the turn as soon as it hands
control back to the user, even if a background job is still running. What
worked: asking the agent to run several short foreground commands
sequentially (`sleep 8` x4, ~32-50s total foreground wall time), which kept
the turn open long enough to cross the 30s distill threshold (confirmed via
`.container-state/<profile>/tenex/edge/logs/distill.log`).

## The `edge-distillation` LLM role can be misconfigured to an unreachable local endpoint, and `explain` correctly reports "not distill-driven" for a failed distill

In this host's `~/.tenex-edge/llms.json` (projected read-only into the
container at `/host-auth/tenex-edge/llms.json`), the `edge-distillation`
role resolves to `ollama/deepseek-v4-flash:cloud`, which attempts
`http://localhost:8081/api/chat` â€” unreachable from inside the container
(the reachable Ollama endpoint is `OLLAMA_HOST=http://192.168.64.1:11434`,
used successfully by other roles/doctor checks). Result:
`distill error: ollama/deepseek-v4-flash:cloud prompt failed: ... error
sending request for url (http://localhost:8081/api/chat)`, followed by a
graceful `falling back to nudge-to-keep`. `tenex-edge explain event:<id>` on
the resulting status publish correctly prints `LLM inputs: (none â€” this
publish was not distill-driven)` â€” this matches `src/distill.rs`'s
`distill_session`, which only produces a `DistillCapture` (and therefore a
queryable `llm_calls` row) on a *successful* model round-trip; an `Err` path
falls through to nudge-to-keep with `capture = None`. So `explain` is
behaving correctly here â€” the gap is host LLM-role config, not the
reconciler/explain code.

## `scripts/cleanup-lab` now relies on cidfiles and the relay PID

The cleanup helper no longer scans external session names. It reads the
container cidfiles under the lab work directory, stops those containers when the
container runtime is available, and kills the relay PID recorded in `lab.env`.
For a stuck launch-mode PTY, kill it explicitly with the same profile/home
context:

```bash
bash containers/tenex-edge/run --profile claude tenex-edge pty kill <pty-id>
```

### How the LLM-inputs money shot was actually produced (working recipe)

The `$TENEX_EDGE_DISTILL_CMD` override (checked before the `edge-distillation`
role, `src/distill.rs::distill_session` step (a)) pipes the transcript slice to
any external command's stdin and parses `TITLE:`/`NOW:` lines from its stdout.
The capture it records has `provider="command"`, `model=<the command string>`,
and â€” importantly â€” `system_prompt = SESSION_SYSTEM_PROMPT` (the crate constant,
`capture()` hardcodes it regardless of override), so `tenex-edge explain` still
shows the canonical distiller system prompt. Recipe that worked end-to-end:

1. Wrapper script dropped into profile home (bind-mounted at `/state/home`,
   preserved across `write-container-profiles` edge-state resets):
   `.container-state/claude/home/distill-claude.sh` (chmod +x), body:
   ```sh
   #!/bin/sh
   exec claude -p --model haiku --no-session-persistence --disallowedTools '*' \
     --system-prompt '<two-line TITLE:/NOW: instruction>'
   ```
   The transcript arrives on stdin (claude -p reads the prompt from stdin);
   stdout is the two labelled lines. `claude` lives at `/usr/local/bin/claude`,
   which IS on the daemon's restricted PATH, so `Command::new("claude")` /
   `sh -c` both resolve.
2. Passthrough: `containers/tenex-edge/run`'s env allow-list only forwarded
   `ANTHROPIC_*` / `CLAUDE_CODE_*`. Added `TENEX_EDGE_DISTILL_CMD` to that loop
   (one line) so a host-set value reaches the container daemon's env.
3. Inject at launch: pty swallows the current shell env when a server already
   exists, so set it explicitly with `pty new-session -e`:
   ```bash
   pty new-session -d -s <sess> -e TENEX_EDGE_DISTILL_CMD='sh /state/home/distill-claude.sh' \
     "cd <repo> && env TENEX_EDGE_CONTAINER_NAME=<sess> TENEX_EDGE_CONTAINER_CIDFILE=<cid> \
      bash containers/tenex-edge/run --profile claude tenex-edge launch claude -- --model haiku"
   ```
4. Drive a >30s turn with real content, e.g. "Read src/distill.rs,
   src/explain.rs, src/instrument.rs and one-line each, then run 'sleep 8 &&
   echo tN' four times sequentially, then say finished." The reads give the
   model real TITLE/NOW material; the four foreground sleeps guarantee the
   turn crosses the 30s distill threshold.
5. `distill.log` then shows `using TENEX_EDGE_DISTILL_CMD override` with NO
   `distill error` / `falling back` line, and the 30315 gains
   `title="Build transcript distillation and query system"` +
   `content="Reading source code and executing commands"`.
6. STOP the agent (same-profile RPC lesson), then:
   - `tenex-edge explain session:<sid>` â†’ latest llm_call + the status
     receipt(s) sharing its `window_hash` (the receipt's `artifact_ref` is the
     exact distill-driven 30315 id).
   - `tenex-edge explain event:<that-30315-id>` â†’ the join, headed
     `LLM inputs â€” what was fed to the model so it said this:` with
     provider/model, window_hash, parsed title/activity, the full system
     prompt, the fed transcript slice, and the raw `TITLE:`/`NOW:` response.
   - `tenex-edge explain llm:<row-id>` â†’ the same call by row id (reverse
     join to its status receipts).

Two gotchas seen: (i) the override's `CommandDistiller::run_all` uses a
*blocking* `std::process::Command`; while the `claude -p` distiller subprocess
runs (cold start can take ~1-2 min end to end here), the statusline briefly
reads `[te: down]` because the blocking call ties up the async worker â€” it
recovers on completion and is NOT a failure. (ii) Only the `on_distill`
publish (the one whose title/activity changed) carries `window_hash` in its
receipt; later TTL heartbeat republishes carry the same title but drive with
`None` window_hash, so `explain event:` on those shows "not distill-driven".
Use the receipt list from `explain session:` to pick the right event id.

The durable fix for the underlying gap is still worthwhile: either repair the
host `edge-distillation` role to point at a reachable model (it currently
resolves to `ollama/deepseek-v4-flash:cloud` â†’ `http://localhost:8081`, which
is unreachable in-container), or keep `TENEX_EDGE_DISTILL_CMD` in the run
allow-list (done in this worktree) so labs can force a working distiller
without touching host config.
